In [the ILM documentation](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/ilm-readonly.html#) we mention;

> Makes the index [read-only](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/index-modules.html#dynamic-index-settings).

However in that link there's no mention of what setting is the actual read-only one. And looking through them I am not sure this is the correct reference. Should it be pointing to [`index.blocks.read_only`](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/index-modules-blocks.html#index-block-settings) instead?

**Elasticsearch version**: 7.9.0 on Elastic Cloud, verified on local official Docker image
**Plugins installed**: _N/A_

**Description of the problem including expected versus actual behavior**:
Performing a search that includes a terms aggregation with `min_doc_count: 0` and any sub-aggregation, where the query ensures that buckets with a doc count of 0 will exist, returns a `search_phase_execution_exception` with a root cause of `array_index_out_of_bounds_exception`.

This behaviour was not present in 7.8.1, and is still present in 7.9.1. The previous (and expected) behaviour was for the sub-aggregations to proceed as if on an empty context.

**Steps to reproduce**:
These steps reproduce the problem on a fresh cluster. So far as I can tell, _any_ aggregation under `subagg` will return the same error - not just the filter/match_all in this example.

```
PUT /bug-mre

PUT /bug-mre/_mapping
{
  "properties": {
    "letter": {
      "type": "keyword"
    }
  }
}

POST /bug-mre/_bulk
{"index":{}}
{"letter":"a"}
{"index":{}}
{"letter":"b"}

GET /bug-mre/_search
{
  "query": {
    "term": {
      "letter": "a"
    }
  },
  "aggs": {
    "letters": {
      "terms": {
        "field": "letter",
        "min_doc_count": 0
      },
      "aggs": {
        "subagg": {
          "filter": {
            "match_all": {}
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

This returns:

```
{
  "error" : {
    "root_cause" : [
      {
        "type" : "array_index_out_of_bounds_exception",
        "reason" : "Index -1 out of bounds for length 1"
      }
    ],
    "type" : "search_phase_execution_exception",
    "reason" : "all shards failed",
    "phase" : "query",
    "grouped" : true,
    "failed_shards" : [
      {
        "shard" : 0,
        "index" : "bug-mre",
        "node" : "vuf3AdPqQV--8ZHh5QiYrA",
        "reason" : {
          "type" : "array_index_out_of_bounds_exception",
          "reason" : "Index -1 out of bounds for length 1"
        }
      }
    ],
    "caused_by" : {
      "type" : "array_index_out_of_bounds_exception",
      "reason" : "Index -1 out of bounds for length 1",
      "caused_by" : {
        "type" : "array_index_out_of_bounds_exception",
        "reason" : "Index -1 out of bounds for length 1"
      }
    }
  },
  "status" : 500
}

```

Please let me know if you'd like any more info!

To reproduce:
```
DELETE test

PUT test
{
  "mappings" : {
    "properties" : {
      "my_val" : {
        "type" : "double"
      }
    }
  }
}

PUT test/_doc/1
{
  "my_val": 0.2
}

PUT test/_doc/2
{
  "my_val": 0.4
}

PUT test/_doc/3
{
  "my_val": 0.6
}

POST test/_search
{
  "size": 0,
  "aggs": {
    "without": {
      "histogram": {
        "field": "my_val",
        "interval": 0.1
      }
    },
    "with": {
      "histogram": {
        "field": "my_val",
        "interval": 0.1,
        "hard_bounds": {
          "min": 0.3,
          "max": 0.5
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```
When hard_bounds are added it produces 0 buckets. It works as expected if I multiply bounds by 10, so I suspect it might have something to do with double type conversion/comparison. Will investigate.

**Elasticsearch version** (`bin/elasticsearch --version`):
7.9.1 (from official docker image)
**Description of the problem including expected versus actual behavior**:
allow_leading_wildcard false prevent a search in 7.9.0 which runs in 7.9.1
**Steps to reproduce**:
Run this in Kibana Dev tool:
```
PUT testwildcard/_doc/1
{
  "foo": "bar"
}

POST testwildcard/_search
{
  "query": {
    "query_string": {
      "query": "*ar",
      "fields": [
        "foo"
      ],
      "allow_leading_wildcard": false
    }
  }
}
```

In 7.9.1, the document is returned, the output in 7.9.0 (and lower versions) does block the search from running as expected: 
```
{
  "error" : {
    "root_cause" : [
      {
        "type" : "query_shard_exception",
        "reason" : "Failed to parse query [*ar]",
        "index_uuid" : "UmDK7qc_Sqef6uhk-f0fWA",
        "index" : "testwildcard"
      }
    ],
    "type" : "search_phase_execution_exception",
    "reason" : "all shards failed",
    "phase" : "query",
    "grouped" : true,
    "failed_shards" : [
      {
        "shard" : 0,
        "index" : "testwildcard",
        "node" : "zyyjFmpWQnK4NE9VXPn_ng",
        "reason" : {
          "type" : "query_shard_exception",
          "reason" : "Failed to parse query [*ar]",
          "index_uuid" : "UmDK7qc_Sqef6uhk-f0fWA",
          "index" : "testwildcard",
          "caused_by" : {
            "type" : "parse_exception",
            "reason" : "Cannot parse '*ar': '*' or '?' not allowed as first character in WildcardQuery",
            "caused_by" : {
              "type" : "parse_exception",
              "reason" : "'*' or '?' not allowed as first character in WildcardQuery"
            }
          }
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "status" : 400
}
```

For ref : 
- [7.9.1 release notes](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/7.9/release-notes-7.9.1.html)
- [doc](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/query-dsl-query-string-query.html) : `analyze_wildcard (Optional, boolean) If true, the query attempts to analyze wildcard terms in the query string. Defaults to false.`

